            "product_text_content_1": "<p>If you want something familiar and basic, go for the block chalk. Better yet, go for one of the best block chalks on the market – the <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/PICSIL-Magnesium-Gymnastics-Weightlifting-Crosstraining/dp/B07QQ1MYCN/?tag=wbcmb-20\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://www.amazon.com/PICSIL-Magnesium-Gymnastics-Weightlifting-Crosstraining/dp/B07QQ1MYCN/?tag=wbcmb-20\">Picsil Chalk Block</a>.</p><p>This chalk doesn’t have the best packaging, because as soon as you receive it, you may notice some chalk dust outside. Then, when you open it, there’s a decent amount of dust coming out of it. This is pretty standard for block chalks, but if you have respiratory issues, be careful not to inhale it. </p><p>Although it’s quite dusty, its performance is great. It lasts a long time even in humidity and the grip it provides is phenomenal. You can count on this chalk to have your back (or… your hands) no matter how much you sweat. It doesn’t flake off and it doesn’t transfer too much. Its formula is clean and good quality, and everything about this is really straightforward – no unnecessary bells and whistles, just your basic block chalk that does what it’s supposed to do and doesn’t need to be reapplied frequently. </p><p>Although it’s great at sweat absorption, you don’t have to worry about it being too harsh on your skin and drying your hands out. It’s always good to apply some moisturizer on your hands after chalk use, but compared to liquid chalks, this one is gentle to the skin.</p><p>The only thing that could use some improvement is the packaging, because the box isn’t that secure and some of the powder does get out, but other than that, there’s not much to complain about.</p>",
